library(ggplot2)

Reading in the dataset

births <- read.csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/azkajavaid/data/master/births/US_births_1994-2003_CDC_NCHS.csv")

# Analyzing births over year 
births_over_year <- births %>% group_by(year) %>% summarise(total_births = sum(births))
ggplot(data = births_over_year, aes(x = year, y = total_births)) + geom_line(color = "#FC4E07") + theme_bw() + ggtitle("Total Population Over Time")

### Total number of births decrease

Analyzing births over month

births_over_month <- births %>% group_by(month) %>% summarise(total_births_month = sum(births))
ggplot(data = births_over_month, aes(x = month, y = total_births_month)) + geom_line(color = "#FC4E07") + theme_bw() + ggtitle("Total Population Over Months")

Analyzing births over day of week

births_over_dayofweek <- births %>% group_by(day_of_week) %>% summarise(total_births_week = sum(births))
ggplot(data = births_over_dayofweek, aes(x = day_of_week, y = total_births_week)) + geom_line(color = "#FC4E07") + theme_bw() + ggtitle("Total Population Over Months")

### There appears to be an increase in the total number of births in the beginning of week followed by a decrease on the fifth, sixth and seven days.

combine with yearly financial/economic indicator data

adding in financial data from the balance.com (https://www.thebalance.com/us-gdp-by-year-3305543)

ninety_four_vector <- c(7.287, 10.352, 4.0)
ninety_five_vector <- c(7.640, 10.630, 2.7)
ninety_six_vector <- c(8.073, 11.031, 3.8)
ninety_seven_vector <- c(8.578, 11.522, 4.4)
ninety_eight_vector <- c(9.063, 12.038, 4.5)
ninety_nine_vector <- c(9.631, 12.611, 4.8)
two_thousand_vector <- c(10.252, 13.131, 4.1)
two_thousand_one_vector <- c(10.582, 13.262, 1.0)
two_thousand_two_vector <- c(10.936, 13.493, 1.7)
two_thousand_three_vector <- c(11.458, 13.879, 2.9)

economic_indicators <- data.frame(t(data.frame(ninety_four_vector, ninety_five_vector, ninety_six_vector,
                        ninety_seven_vector, ninety_eight_vector, ninety_nine_vector,
                        two_thousand_vector, two_thousand_one_vector, two_thousand_two_vector,
                        two_thousand_three_vector)))
colnames(economic_indicators) <- c("NominalGDP", "RealGDP", "GDPGrowthRate")
rownames(economic_indicators) <- c("1994", "1995", "1996", "1997", "1998", "1999", "2000",
                                   "2001", "2002", "2003")

economic_indicators_update <- setDT(economic_indicators, keep.rownames = TRUE)[]
colnames(economic_indicators_update)[1] <- "year"
economic_indicators_update$year <- as.character(economic_indicators_update$year)
births$year <- as.character(births$year)
births2 <- births %>% inner_join(economic_indicators_update)
## Joining, by = "year"
head(births2)

births2$month <- as.factor(births2$month)

generating training and test data

k-fold cross-validation

mod1 <- lm(births ~ NominalGDP + RealGDP + GDPGrowthRate + day_of_week + month + date_of_month, data = births2)
summary(mod1)
